SIMPLE: seeming
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seeming
<hw>Seem"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a semblance, whether with
or without reality; apparent; specious; befitting; <as>as,
<ex>seeming</ex> friendship; <ex>seeming</ex> truth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My lord, you have lost a friend indeed;⟦br⟧
And I dare swear you borrow not that face⟦br⟧
Of <qex>seeming</qex> sorrow, it is sure your own.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seeming</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seeming
<hw>Seem"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Appearance; show;
semblance; fair appearance; speciousness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These keep⟦br⟧
<qex>Seeming</qex> and savor all the winter long.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Apprehension; judgment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing more clear unto their <qex>seeming</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His persuasive words, impregned⟦br⟧
With reason, to her <qex>seeming</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seemingly</ent>⟦br⟧
